data.value: API = Usually refers to REST APIs (data layer of the application)
Analytics = data statistics (usually refers to user data)
Algorithm = Code that solves a specific problem (usually refers to a business problem)
Bug = Something within the App that does not work correctly
Backlog = List of tasks that need to be done
Cookie = Data stored on your device when visting a web site
Code = Computer Code (Instructions for the computer)
Customer = The person that uses the App
Clean Code = Code that is easy to read and work it
Deploy = Make the App available to the public
Debug = Find out why the App is not working as intended
Desktop = Standard/Traditional PC (Not a smartphone, tablet or any other smart device)
Data Type = The variable type (Int, String, Boolean)
Encryption = Make text unreadable/cryptic for security reasons
E-commerce = Selling of goods or services using the internet
Fetch = Fetch Data from Internet / Fetch API (Improved XMLHttpRequest)
Full Stack = Full Stack Developer (A person that knows both frontend and backend technologies)
Framework = A tool to improve/simplify programming
Feature = An important function of the App
Globals = Global variables (variables that can be accessed all over)
Hosting = Make your App available online by paying a web hosting company
Hooks = Web Hooks (A Http Request triggered by an event)
Iaas = Infrastructure as a Service (Rentable servers with developer tools)
JSON = A common way to format data
Kanban = A post-it note board used to organize your project
Load Balancing = A system that prevents the app from crashing by managing/distributing the workload
Legacy = Legacy Code (Code from a old project)
Microservices = Many small Applications working as one
Native = Technologies natural to the environment (environment = OS)
Open Source = The code (source code) of the App is available for everyone
Outsource = Let another company do the job to save costs
Production = App has been released to the public
Paas = Platform as a Service (Cloud hosting with developer tools)
Pipeline = Deployment Pipeline (The automated process of deploying the App)
Parse = To filter / structure / convert data
Port = Make app available on a new platform
Polyfill = Code that provides new web browser functionality to old web browsers
Preload = Prepare something by loading it before it's being used
Params = Parameters (Usually refers to values taken by a function)
Rate Limit = Limit the number of requests someone can send
Stack = Tech Stack (The techonologies used to build the App)
Saas = Software as a Service (Apps/Tools available online that cost money)
Scale = Increase the amount of users the App can handle
Token = Verification Token (Used as a password to gain access to something)
Telemetry = Collection of technical data by the app (Usually refers to performance data)
Transpiler = Converts one programming language to another
UI = User Interface (The look of the App)
UX = User Experience (The feel of the App)
User Agent = User Device Info (Used to identify your device on the web)
View = A section of the App
Web = World Wide Web / Web Browser / Website

data.name: Meteor
data.comment:
Meteor
Meteor is an open source framework for seamlessly building and deploying Web, Mobile, and Desktop applications in Javascript.

data.name: Kivy
data.comment:
Kivy
Open source Python library for rapid development of applications that make use of innovative user interfaces, such as multi-touch apps.

data.name: Express.js
data.comment: Express.js, or simply Express, is a back end web application framework for Node.js, released as free and open-source software under the MIT License. It is designed for building web applications and APIs. It has been called the de facto standard server framework for Node.js.

data.name: Lodash
data.comment:
Lodash
Lodash is a JavaScript library which provides utility functions for common programming tasks using the functional programming paradigm.
